      "FIFO stands for First In First Out. The Income Tax Department requires you to use this method when calculating capital gains from mutual fund redemptions. It means: when you sell units, you are treated as selling the oldest units first.",
      "Here is a simple example. You did SIPs of Rs 5,000 per month for 12 months in Fund A. That is 12 separate buy lots, each at a different NAV. After 14 months, you redeemed half your units. Under FIFO, your redemption is matched against Lot 1 first, then Lot 2, and so on until all the redeemed units are accounted for.",
      "Why this matters for tax: Units held for more than 12 months qualify for LTCG treatment (taxed at 12.5% above Rs 1.25 lakh for equity funds). Units held for less than 12 months are STCG (taxed at 20% for equity funds). Since FIFO uses your oldest lots first, more of your redemption will likely qualify as LTCG -- which is the lower tax rate. But only if you track it correctly.",
      "The register problem: In a register, doing FIFO manually means going back through every single purchase entry, checking the date, calculating the holding period for that lot against your sale date, determining STCG or LTCG, and calculating the gain for that lot individually. For 24 monthly SIP entries across 4 funds, that is up to 96 individual calculations.",
      "Errors in this process mean the wrong ITR. An understated gain means tax liability you are hiding (even unintentionally). An overstated gain means you pay more tax than you owe. Neither is acceptable.",
      "A portfolio management tool runs FIFO automatically. Every sell transaction is matched against the correct buy lots in the correct order, with the correct holding period, applying the correct tax rate. The capital gains report is accurate and ready to copy into your ITR.",
