      "Long-term capital gains on equity mutual funds are taxed at ten percent without indexation for gains exceeding one lakh rupees per year. Short-term capital gains are taxed at fifteen percent. The difference in tax rates is significant -- and the boundary is the one-year holding period. Knowing exactly when each purchase lot crosses that boundary gives you the opportunity to plan redemptions tax-efficiently.",
      "In theory, you could build an Excel column that shows the one-year anniversary date for each purchase lot. Many investors do this. The problem is that this column is passive -- it shows you data but does not alert you when a boundary is approaching. You have to remember to check it regularly, and most people do not.",
      "The practical result is that investors redeem units without checking whether they are just days or weeks away from the LTCG threshold. A purchase made on March 15 in one year, redeemed on March 10 the following year, is five days short of LTCG qualification. The gain that would have been taxed at ten percent is instead taxed at fifteen percent. For large redemptions, this is a meaningful difference.",
      "A well-designed portfolio management tool surfaces this information proactively. You can see at a glance which lots are approaching their one-year anniversary. Before making a redemption, you know the tax consequence. You can choose to wait a few more days or weeks to qualify for the lower LTCG rate.",
